President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring March 2011 as Irish-American Heritage Month. The proclamation highlights the contributions of Irish Americans to the United States and recognizes the shared history and friendship between Ireland and the United States. It acknowledges the hardships faced by Irish immigrants and their role in building strong communities and shaping the nation. The proclamation also pays tribute to President John F. Kennedy, the first Irish-American Catholic President, and other Irish Americans who have played leadership roles in the country. The proclamation calls upon all Americans to celebrate the contributions of Irish Americans during this month.